.TH RANX 1 "November 2025" "ranx 1.0.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
ranx \- display random numbers using parallel generation
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ranx
[\fIOPTION\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Write random numbers to standard output using the high-performance ranx library.
.PP
The ranx utility generates random numbers using the PCG32 (Permuted Congruential
Generator) engine with TRNG statistical distributions. It supports parallel
generation and guarantees reproducible sequences when using the same seed.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-N \fIcount\fR
The count of random numbers to generate (default: 1)
.TP
.B \-M\fR, \fB\-\-max \fInumber\fR
The maximum value for random numbers (default: 32576)
.TP
.B \-u\fR, \fB\-\-unique
Generate unique numbers without duplicate values. Note that count cannot exceed max+1.
.TP
.B \-f
Generate floating-point numbers between 0 and 1
.TP
.B \-p \fIprecision\fR
Set the decimal precision for floating-point numbers (activates \-f)
.TP
.B \-s \fInumber\fR
Set the seed for the random number generator. Using the same seed produces
identical sequences. Default is based on current time.
.TP
.B \-d \fISTRING\fR
Set the delimiter between numbers (default: space). Supports escape sequences
like \\n for newline and \\t for tab.
.TP
.B \-\-bof \fISTRING\fR
String to print at the beginning of output (default: nothing)
.TP
.B \-\-eof \fISTRING\fR
String to print at the end of output (default: newline)
.TP
.B \-\-help
Display help message and exit
.TP
.B \-\-version
Output version information and exit
.SH EXAMPLES
Generate 10 random numbers:
.PP
.nf
.RS
ranx \-N 10
.RE
.fi
.PP
Generate 5 random numbers between 0 and 100:
.PP
.nf
.RS
ranx \-N 5 \-M 100
.RE
.fi
.PP
Generate 10 unique numbers from 0 to 20:
.PP
.nf
.RS
ranx \-N 10 \-u \-M 20
.RE
.fi
.PP
Generate 5 floating-point numbers with 4 decimal places:
.PP
.nf
.RS
ranx \-f \-p 4 \-N 5
.RE
.fi
.PP
Generate numbers separated by commas:
.PP
.nf
.RS
ranx \-N 5 \-d ", "
.RE
.fi
.PP
Generate reproducible sequence with a specific seed:
.PP
.nf
.RS
ranx \-N 10 \-s 42
.RE
.fi
.PP
Format output as a JSON array:
.PP
.nf
.RS
ranx \-N 5 \-d ", " \-\-bof "[" \-\-eof "]"
.RE
.fi
.SH REPRODUCIBILITY
When the same seed is provided with the \fB\-s\fR option, ranx guarantees
identical output across multiple runs:
.PP
.nf
.RS
$ ranx \-N 5 \-s 123
27606 20324 14982 6188 27424

$ ranx \-N 5 \-s 123
27606 20324 14982 6188 27424
.RE
.fi
.PP
This reproducibility is maintained across different platforms and thread counts,
unlike many other random number generators.
.SH PERFORMANCE
The ranx utility uses parallel generation with OpenMP, providing high performance
even for large datasets. Typical performance: ~100,000 numbers in 30ms on modern
hardware.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success
.TP
.B 1
Invalid command-line arguments or impossible parameters (e.g., requesting more
unique numbers than the range allows)
.SH TECHNICAL DETAILS
.TP
.B Random Number Engine
PCG32 (Permuted Congruential Generator) providing excellent statistical
properties, fast generation speed, and small state size
.TP
.B Distributions
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Integers: trng::uniform_int_dist for uniform integer distribution
.IP \(bu 2
Floats: trng::uniform01_dist for uniform distribution between 0 and 1
.IP \(bu 2
Unique values: Fisher-Yates shuffle via std::shuffle with PCG32
.RE
